The differential equation is separable; that is,

\begin{align*}
\frac{dy}{dx}=(y^2-1)x\implies \int \frac{1}{y^2-1} \, dy = \int x\, dx.
\end{align*}

On the right hand side,

\begin{align*}
\int x\, dx = \frac{x^2}2+C_1,
\end{align*}

for some constant $C_1.$ On the left hand side, we factor
$y^2-1 = (y+1)(y-1)$ and use partial fractions.

\begin{align*}
&\frac1{(y+1)(y-1)}=\frac{A}{y+1}+\frac{B}{y-1}\\
 &\implies 1=A(y-1)+B(y+1).
\end{align*}

This must be true for all $y$. In particular, at $y=-1$ , $1=-2A$,
hence, $A=-1/2$. At $y=1$, $1=2B$, hence $B=1/2$. Therefore,

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{1}{y^2-1}\, dy& =- \frac12 \int \frac{1}{y+1}\, dy +\frac12\int \frac{1}{y-1}\,dy\\
& =- \frac12 \ln|y+1| +\frac12\ln|y-1| +C_2\\
& =\frac12 \ln\left|\frac{y-1}{y+1}\right| +C_2,
\end{align*}

for some constant $C_2.$ The initial condition is $y(0)=0,$ so at least
for small $x$ , we know that $-1<y(x)<1$. This means that \emph{y}-1 is
negative and \emph{y}+1 is positive. Hence

\[\left|\frac{y-1}{y+1}\right| = - \frac{y-1}{y+1} = \frac{1-y}{y+1} = \frac{1-y}{1+y}.\]

Therefore

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{1}{y^2-1}\, dy
& =\frac12 \ln\left(\frac{1-y}{1+y}\right) +C_2.
\end{align*}

Equating the left and right sides of our first equation, we have

\begin{align*}
&\frac12 \ln\left(\frac{1-y}{1+y}\right) =  \frac{x^2}2+ C_1-C_2\\
&\implies \frac{1-y}{1+y} =  A e^{x^2}\\
&\implies 1-y= (1+y) A e^{x^2}\\
&\implies 1- A e^{x^2}= y(1+ A e^{x^2})\\
&\implies y= \frac{1- A e^{x^2}}{1+ A e^{x^2}}.
\end{align*}

where $A=e^{2(C_1-C_2)}$. From the initial condition, $y(0)=0$, $A$ must
be equal to 1. Hence,

\begin{align*}
 y(x)= \frac{1- e^{x^2}}{1+ e^{x^2}}.
\end{align*}

Note that this solution does satisfy $-1<y(x)<1$ for all $x$.

Remember: It is important (and usually easy) to check that your solution
actually satisfies the differential equation.
